"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711466","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>NHS Property Services has provided information relating to the previous known usage of properties (by county) currently classified as vacant in the attached table.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-20T16:21:04.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711466/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711466/answer","PQ68208 attached table.xlsx","PQ68208 attached table.xlsx","PQ68208","PQ68208","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711466/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","NHS: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 13 March 2017 to Question 66957, on NHS: buildings, which of the buildings listed are in each county.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","68208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711467","Department of Health","false","2017-03-24","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The North West London Collaboration of Clinical Commissioning Groups has published information on their website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.healthiernorthwestlondon.nhs.uk/document-downloads" target="_blank">http://www.healthiernorthwestlondon.nhs.uk/document-downloads</a></p><p> </p><p>which relates to the establishment of the programme, and includes copies of governance papers.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-24T12:44:36.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711467/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711467/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","Hospitals: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the public purse was of the public consultation for the Shaping a Healthier Future programme undertaken in north west London in 2012.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","68145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711468","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-24","<p>The Government is clear that the £2 billion announced on 8 March for social care must be spent only for the purpose of meeting adult social care needs, including reducing pressures on the NHS, supporting more people to be discharged from hospital when they are ready, and ensuring that the local social care provider market is supported. The money will be provided as a grant to councils with conditions attached to ensure it is spent for this purpose.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-24T12:07:46.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711468/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711468/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 6.1 of the Spring Budget 2017, what steps he plans to take to ensure that the £2 billion for social care will be delivered to frontline services and not subsumed by other council expenditure.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","68146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711469","Department of Health","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Government is committed to establishing a fairer, more sustainable basis for funding adult social care, in the face of the future demographic challenges the country faces. We will bring forward proposals in a green paper later this year to put the state funded system on a more secure long-term footing. The Secretary of State for Health, his ministerial team, and officials meet regularly with stakeholders from the voluntary sector. We intend to build on and continue this engagement in developing our proposals. Once published the green paper will provide further opportunity for people across the sector to consider and respond to our proposals.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-21T10:31:47.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711469/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711469/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","Social Services: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 6.1 of the Spring Budget 2017, if the Government will engage with third sector organisations and charities during the consultation process for the social care green paper.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","68147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711470","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>Although data on general practitioner (GP) practices is collected by NHS Business Services Authority and published for use in the National Health Service by NHS Digital, data on practice closures cannot distinguish between practices which have closed and those which have merged or been taken over. In addition, changes to definitions of GP practices for data purposes mean that it is not possible to produce meaningful figures relating to closures over a period of years.</p><p> </p><p>The issues around this data collection do not affect NHS services in any way. NHS England works with the Care Quality Commission and clinical commissioning groups to assess local primary care provision in an area and to ensure that appropriate services are available.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","68169","2017-03-20T16:47:00.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711470/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711470/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","General Practitioners: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 28 February 2017 to Question 65408, on general practitioners: closures, what assessment he has made of the effect that not collecting centrally data on practice closures has on his Department's fulfilment of its responsibilities and priorities to improve services through the use of digital technology, information and transparency.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","68170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711471","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>Question 65127 requested data from 2012-13 onwards. The table below shows the estimated cost of tooth extractions for all patients in hospitals from 2010-11 to 2011-12. The data covers all tooth extractions/removals.</p><p> </p><p>Reference costs are the average unit costs to National Health Service trusts and NHS foundation trusts of providing defined services in a given financial year to NHS patients. Reference costs for acute care are collected by healthcare resource group, which are standard groupings of clinically similar treatments which use common levels of healthcare resource.</p><p> </p><p>Reference Costs: Tooth extractions/removals 2010-11 to 2011-12</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Estimated total cost £ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Extractions/Removal for all patients</p></td><td><p>109.8</p></td><td><p>114.4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Department of Health, Reference Costs</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-20T16:49:20.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711471/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711471/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2017 to Question 65127, on dental services, for what reason no date has been provided in that Answer for the years 2010-11 and 2011-12 for tooth extractions and removal for all patients.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","68167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711472","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>NHS England, following engagement with national key stakeholders, agreed on a fair shares distribution of funds to each NHS England local team footprint. Each fair share of the £16 million allocation was calculated using patient population registered for general practice services in that area, relative to the national registered patient population. This ensures the allocation of funds to support general practice reflects the needs for general practice services in each area.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-20T16:45:07.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711472/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711472/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","General Practitioners: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2017 to Question 65202, on general practitioners: finance, what procedures NHS England followed to distribute those funds.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","68168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711473","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>Although data on general practitioner (GP) practices is collected by NHS Business Services Authority and published for use in the National Health Service by NHS Digital, data on practice closures cannot distinguish between practices which have closed and those which have merged or been taken over. In addition, changes to definitions of GP practices for data purposes mean that it is not possible to produce meaningful figures relating to closures over a period of years.</p><p> </p><p>The issues around this data collection do not affect NHS services in any way. NHS England works with the Care Quality Commission and clinical commissioning groups to assess local primary care provision in an area and to ensure that appropriate services are available.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","68170","2017-03-20T16:47:00.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711473/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711473/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","General Practitioners: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 28 February 2017 to Question 65408, on general practitioners: closures, for what reasons his Department does not collect centrally data on practice closures.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","68169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711474","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>NHS Digital publishes information on the number of nursing, midwifery and health visiting staff employed in the National Health Service in England each month.</p><p> </p><p>As at September 2010, there were 7,849 full-time equivalent health visitors working in the NHS Hospital and Community Health Service workforce.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T17:07:31.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711474/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711474/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","Health Visitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many health visitors were employed in NHS trusts and clinical commissioning groups in England in 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","68118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711475","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>The number of mother and baby beds is not collected routinely. NHS England is leading work to create four new 8-bedded mother and baby units in areas with particular access issues. The procurement process for these units is underway and will mean that by 2020, 30,000 more women will have access to care every year. A number of different reports provides the number of beds included in the following table.</p><p> </p><p>Mother and Baby beds in England</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of beds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>118</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>123</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>115</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>2010 data from National Perinatal Mental Health Project Report, March 2011</p><p>2013 data from NHS England Service Specification 2013</p><p>2015 NHS England National Expert Reference Group Report 2015</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T16:56:22.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711475/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711475/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-15","Baby Care Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many mother and baby beds were available in mental health units or hospitals in England in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","68131"
