"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710848","Department for Education","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Department has no central record of any staff having been seconded to it from PwC, Deloitte, Accenture, McKinsey &amp; Co, Ernst and Young or Bain &amp; Company since July 2016. It is not possible to verify that there are no secondees from these organisations, as secondments can be agreed by individual managers and may not always be notified to the central HR team.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-20T17:53:38.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710848/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710848/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-14","Department for Education: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff have been seconded to her Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710849","Department for Education","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Department is taking action to reduce the number of borrowers due to repay who are not repaying their loans.</p><p>If borrowers based overseas fail to remain in contact with the SLC, the SLC will set up a fixed repayment schedule and will place those borrowers in arrears. Borrowers with post-2012 loans who have not remained in contact with the SLC are charged the maximum interest rate of RPI+3% until they get back in touch. Further action, including legal action, can then be taken to secure recovery. The SLC established a dedicated Repayments Evasion Unit in 2016 to detect borrowers overseas who fail to comply with their statutory obligations to repay their loans.</p><p>The Department published a Joint Repayment Strategy in February 2016, which sets out how action will be taken to trace borrowers and act to recover loans where avoidance or evasion is identified. This publication can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/student-loan-repayment-strategy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/student-loan-repayment-strategy</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-03-21T16:18:24.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710849/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710849/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-14","Overseas Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2017 to Question 65926, on overseas students: loans, if she will take steps to reduce the number of borrowers who have not repaid their loans.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","67717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710850","Department for Education","false","2017-04-03","<p>The total amount loaned out as English student loans in the financial year 2015-16 increased by 11% compared to the financial year 2014-15 due to increasing numbers of students receiving support and a higher proportion of those students being entitled to more financial support as they are on post-2012 tuition fee loan arrangements.</p><p>The main reason the outstanding balance of English student loans was 18% higher at the end of the financial year 2015-16 was that more was loaned out (and therefore added to the outstanding balance) than was repaid in the financial year 2015-16.</p><p>A more complete breakdown of the English student loan book can be found in table 1 of the Student Loans Company (SLC) Statistical First Release (SFR) Student Loans in England.</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-03T07:10:52.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710850/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710850/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-14","Overseas Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2017 to Question 65926, on overseas students: loans, for what reason there was an increase in the outstanding balance from 2014-15 to 2015-16; and for what reasons the 18 per cent increase in the outstanding balance sits alongside an 11 per cent increase in the amount lent.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","67721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710851","Department for Education","false","2017-03-27","<p>Student loan borrowers who are liable to repay their loan and known to be in the UK can be categorised as ‘status that does not require repayment at this point’ for a number of reasons. Most typically these are borrowers who were known by Student Loans Company to have been resident in the UK and had confirmed they were not working, or HMRC or DWP advised that they had been receiving benefits.</p><p>Further information on how the repayment statuses are categorised can be found in the ‘Notes for Users’ section of the Statistical First Release.</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/media/7594/slcsfr012016.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/media/7594/slcsfr012016.pdf</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-03-27T12:59:29.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710851/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710851/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-14","Overseas Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2017 to Question 65926, on overseas students: loans, for what reasons 4.8 per cent of borrowers residing in the UK are not required to repay their student loans.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","67722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710852","Department for Education","false","2017-03-20","<p>We are currently consulting on a national funding formula for schools, and I am engaging widely with honourable members, head teachers, and other representatives on how the proposed formula would affect their areas. Our proposals for funding reform will mean that schools will, for the first time, receive a consistent and fair share of the schools budget, so that they can give every child the opportunity to reach their full potential.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the consultation, we have published impact data of the proposed national funding formulae at school-level for all schools in England on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As a result of our proposals, St Helens North constituency would see an overall increase in schools funding of 1.9%. On funding for pupils with high needs, St. Helens local authority would see an increase of 1.9%.</p><p> </p><p>The current consultation is open until 22 March, and we are keen to hear views from as many schools, governors, local authorities, and parents as possible. We will publish our response to the consultation, including details of representations received, in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-20T09:57:49.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710852/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710852/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-14","Schools: St Helens North","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the school funding formula on the level of funding for schools in St Helens North constituency.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","67705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710853","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>Marine Scotland is already responsible for controlling the activities of all fishing vessels operating within the Scottish zone, as defined by the Fishery Limits Act 1976 and the Scotland Act 1998.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-20T16:03:24.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710853/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710853/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Fisheries: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of devolving powers to the Scottish Government in advance of the Great Repeal Bill in order to promote mixed fisheries opportunities and reactive positive stock management.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","67709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710854","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>As a coastal state outside the EU, the UK will be responsible, under international law, for controlling UK waters and the sustainable management of fisheries resources within the UK’s Exclusive Economic Zone. The UK will negotiate as an independent coastal state.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-20T16:10:54.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710854/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710854/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will take steps to ensure that the UK negotiates future fisheries management as an independent coastal state.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","67710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710855","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, have had no secondees from PwC, Deloitte, Accenture, McKinsey &amp; Co, Ernst and Young or Bain &amp; Company since July 2016.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-22T10:42:47.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710855/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710855/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many staff have been seconded to her Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710856","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-22","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-22T15:50:45.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710856/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710856/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many contracts procured by her Department and its arms-length bodies require that the contractor pays those of its employees undertaking the work contracted for the real living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710857","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-22","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-22T15:53:04.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710857/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710857/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many contracts procured by her Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710858","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-27","<p>In the FCO, Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) regulations (TUPE) are included as standard in commercial contracts. Clauses are excluded only if the specific contract does not require it and this is agreed between the parties. In the last three years, we are only aware of TUPE regulations being applicable in five major contracts (defined as those with a whole life cost of over £15m).</p><p>In the last three years, FCO Services are only aware of TUPE being active in four major contracts (defined as those with a value of more than £2m) , two of which have since expired.</p><p>TUPE has been included as a clause within an additional five major (&gt;£2m) contracts accessed through Crown Commercial frameworks, two of which have since expired.</p><p>Since April 2014, one contract was procured for the British Council in the UK for catering, where TUPE regulations apply.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-27T14:10:23.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710858/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710858/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710859","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>To date the FCO or FCO Services have not included a stipulation to pay the real living wage in any major contract. All contracts include a requirement to pay the National minimum wage and the Foreign Secretary has asked officials to review the FCO's approach to the London Living wage.</p><p>Since April 2014, one contract was procured for the British Council in the UK. All the staff under this contract have been paid the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-23T17:01:14.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710859/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710859/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies require that the contractor pays those of its employees undertaking the work contracted for the real living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710860","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-22","<p>Since July 2016, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office has not had any inward secondments from these companies.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-22T17:28:41.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710860/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710860/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many staff have been seconded to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710861","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-20","<p>It is the longstanding policy of successive British Governments not to comment on intelligence matters. The UK-US relationship is grounded in our history and shared traditions. In both countries, intelligence work takes place within a strong legal framework.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-20T16:46:58.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710861/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710861/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","USA: Intelligence Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make it his policy to review intelligence sharing and joint working with the US.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","67723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710862","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>NHS England publishes data on the performance of ambulance trusts in respect of the number of Category A Red One and Red Two calls responded to within eight minutes and the number of Category A calls resulting in an ambulance arriving at the scene of the incident against the 19 minute standard.</p><p> </p><p>This data is published on a monthly basis at both an England national level and at individual ambulance trust level. Latest data for December 2016 for England and London Ambulance Service NHS Trust is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ambulance-quality-indicators/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ambulance-quality-indicators/</a></p><p> </p><p>Data are not available at constituency or county level.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-20T16:22:53.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710862/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710862/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Ambulance Services: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many time ambulances based in (a) St Helens North constituency, (b) Merseyside and (c) the North West have responded to emergency calls outside the category (i) A and (ii) B response time target in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","67703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710863","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>Since July 2016, one individual from Ernst and Young has been seconded to the Department.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-22T11:06:38.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710863/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710863/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Department of Health: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many staff have been seconded to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710864","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>St Helen’s North constituency is part of the Cheshire and Merseyside Sustainability and Transformation Plan (STP). Information about spend by constituency level is not held centrally or by the STP.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-20T16:34:59.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710864/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710864/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Health Services: St Helens North","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what costs have been (a) incurred to date and (b) committed for future periods for the development and management of sustainability and transformation plans in St Helens North constituency.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","67706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710865","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>No disciplinary action should be taken against medical professionals for raising concerns about standards. In doing so, individuals are protected under the Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-22T16:14:32.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710865/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710865/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","NHS: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what disciplinary actions may be taken against medical professionals who raise concerns on standards.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","67712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710866","Department of Health","false","2017-03-24","<p>Capacity planning is a matter for NHS England. Medway Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) is the lead commissioner for Medway Maritime Hospital and we are advised that local health and care leaders are working through the Kent and Medway Sustainability and Transformation Plan (STP) to ensure that capacity across the STP footprint will meet future need.</p><p> </p><p>The CCG advises that there are currently no commissioning plans, as part of the STP, to reduce capacity at Medway Maritime Hospital.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-24T11:34:12.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710866/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710866/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Medway Maritime Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that Medway Maritime Hospital has capacity to meet the needs of the local population.","false","Biography information for Gordon Henderson","Sittingbourne and Sheppey","Gordon Henderson","67730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710867","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Government believes that people have the right to a higher wage and not be punished by higher taxes. As part of this, from April 2016, we introduced a new mandatory National Living Wage for workers aged 25 and above, and this will rise to £7.50 an hour in 2017. We insist that employers pay at least the National Minimum Wage.</p><p> </p><p>The Department may hold information, however a full and detailed search of all of its contracts it holds would be required and to do so would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Responses from all of the Department’s Non-Departmental Public Bodies and its agencies, including special health authorities are as noted below:</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England has confirmed they hold nil contracts.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital does not hold this information centrally as there is no legal or policy requirement to do so. As such a full search of individual contracts would be required in order to answer this which would be time and cost disproportionate to conduct.</p><p> </p><p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority does not collate this information. To provide an accurate response would involve checking all individual contracts entered into within the last three financial years. This would exceed the cost threshold.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Blood and Transplant does not hold information on the number of contracts which are paid at the Real Living Wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Blood and Transplant currently has a single contract where the National Living Wage is paid.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Business Services Authority has stated the number of contracts awarded in the last three years which contained requirements that contractors pay the real living wage was four.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has stated this information is not collected or held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Health Research Authority has confirmed they hold nil contracts.</p><p>The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) has stated there is no legal requirement though MHRA is currently taking this into account in tenders for new contracts.</p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence has stated to provide an accurate response would involve checking all individual contracts entered into within the last three financial years. They estimate that this would exceed the cost threshold and therefore incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Litigation Authority has stated to provide an accurate response would involve checking all individual contracts entered into within the last three financial years. They estimate that this would exceed the cost threshold and therefore incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>There is no requirement for the Human Tissue Authority to collect and hold this information. To do so would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement does not have any direct contracts (i.e. between Monitor/NHS Trust Development Authority and a supplier) that relate to the type of roles to which the real living wage is applicable.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England (PHE) undertook a process in 2014 to ensure that all staff are being paid a minimum salary equal to, or above, the Living Wage. As such, PHE has no directly employed people earning less than the Living Wage. In 2015, PHE agreed to work with major suppliers to ensure that all outsourced services were paid at Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Quality Commission has stated to provide an accurate response would involve checking all individual contracts entered into within the last three financial years. They estimate that this would exceed the cost threshold and therefore incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-22T17:09:12.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710867/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710867/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Department of Health: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies require that the contractor pays those of its employees undertaking the work contracted for the real living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710868","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Department’s standard terms and conditions over £100,000 include clauses relating to Staff Transfer. To provide a specific number would involve manually checking each contract and therefore would attract a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Responses from all of the Department’s Non-Departmental Public Bodies and its agencies, including special health authorities are as noted below.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital does not hold specific information relating to Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) (TUPE) for its contracts, however, as TUPE is a point of law all contracts are covered by the regulations.</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England have stated it does not hold specific information relating to TUPE for its contracts, however, as TUPE is a point of law all contracts are covered by the regulations.</p><p> </p><p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority does not collate this information. To provide an accurate response would involve checking all individual contracts entered into within the last three financial years. This would exceed the cost threshold.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Blood and Transplant - there are 71 service contracts which have had the potential to incur TUPE costs during the last three years. However NHS Blood and Transplant has not incurred any costs related to these contracts being transferred from one contracted supplier to another.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Blood and Transplant are unable to provide a three yearly breakdown.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Business Services Authority has identified the number of contracts awarded in the last three financial years containing TUPE provisions was 24 and the number of contracts awarded in the last three years which actually involved TUPE was six.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has stated this information is not collected or held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Health Research Authority have confirmed they hold nil contracts.</p><p>The Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency have stated contracts where TUPE regulations have applied include the contract for catering and outsourced work carried out by the Laboratory of the Government Chemist.</p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence have stated to provide an accurate response would involve checking all individual contracts entered into within the last three financial years. They estimate that this would exceed the cost threshold and therefore incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Litigation Authority have stated to provide an accurate response would involve checking all individual contracts entered into within the last three financial years. They estimate that this would exceed the cost threshold and therefore incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>The Human Tissue Authority does not record this information<strong>. </strong>The cost incurred to extract this information would be disproportionate.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement is aware of two contracts (only for Monitor and none for the NHS Trust Development Authority) within the three year financial period where employees were considered to be potentially within scope for TUPE but this was for the suppliers to confirm. NHS Improvement would have to ask each supplier to confirm how many staff actually TUPE’ed on each occasion as they are not ordinarily involved in these detailed discussions as the client. Seeking and receiving confirmation of the actual numbers would take a significant time to confirm. Therefore it is essential to note the contract numbers provided below are potentially covered by TUPE regulations but cannot be confirmed as yet.</p><p>2014/15 – Nil</p><p>2015/16 – One</p><p>2016/17 - One</p><p>Public Health England have confirmed this data is not centrally held.</p><p>The Care Quality Commission have stated to provide an accurate response would involve checking all individual contracts entered into within the last three financial years. They estimate that this would exceed the cost threshold and therefore incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-22T17:11:13.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710868/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710868/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Department of Health: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710869","Home Office","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Home Department does not hold this information centrally.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-03-22T14:33:04.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710869/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710869/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Home Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many contracts procured by her Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710870","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>Home Office requires all of its suppliers to comply with the legal minimum standards of pay as set out in the Government’s National Living Wage legislation. This is a contractual obligation on the supplier and is monitored through contract compliance mechanisms. We do not require or stipulate in our contractual arrangements a requirement to meet the Living Wage Foundation’s real living wage.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government believes that people have the right to a higher wage and not to be punished by higher taxes. As part of this, from April 2016, we introduced a new mandatory National Living Wage (NLW) for workers aged 25 and above, and this will rise to £7.50 an hour in April 2017. We insist that employers pay at least the National Minimum Wage.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-03-23T14:49:44.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710870/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710870/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Home Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many contracts procured by her Department and its arms-length bodies require that the contractor pays those of its employees undertaking the work contracted for the real living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710871","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Home Office are working closely with Freedom from Torture and other key partners to review and make further improvements to the process and training relating to claims involving survivors of torture.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-21T14:55:06.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710871/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710871/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Immigration Officers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what additional training is provided to officials who deal with asylum claimants who are survivors of torture.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","67718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710872","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Home Office has not seconded in any staff from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey &amp; Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain &amp; Company since July 2016.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-03-21T15:15:57.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710872/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710872/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Home Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff have been seconded to her Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710873","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-20","<p>DFID has not seconded anyone in from PwC, Deloitte, Accenture, McKinsey &amp; Co, Ernst and Young or Bain &amp; Company since July 2016.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-20T16:54:06.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710873/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710873/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-14","Department for International Development: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many staff have been seconded to her Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710874","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-20","<p>The UK’s bilateral funding to the Palestinian Authority education sector only goes to support the salaries of vetted teachers and public servants. Our support is helping around 25,000 young Palestinians go to school each year.. The UK is about to assess performance of this past year’s support with the Palestinian Authority, including progress against the Partnership Principles, and tackling incitement in education. DFID OPTs regularly monitors programme performance, including through annual reviews. The Minister of State has also personally reviewed our educational programs on his most recent visit to Palestine and will be contributing to our portfolio review.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-20T16:49:12.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710874/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710874/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-14","Palestinians: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to review her Department's spending on all education projects in the Palestine authority to ensure those projects meet her Department's criteria.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","67713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710875","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-21","<p>All UK-funded aid is distributed on the basis of need irrespective of race, religion or ethnicity. A very wide range of individuals, across all faiths, benefit from this assistance.</p><p>All faith groups can access and receive funding through DFID’s major civil society funding mechanisms: UK Aid Direct and UK Aid Match. Those already in receipt of this funding include: CAFOD, Christian Aid, Samaritans Purse and Habitat for Humanity.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-21T18:05:37.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710875/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710875/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-14","Developing Countries: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what financial assistance her Department gives to Christians in developing countries; and what assistance can be given to individual Christians within the criteria set by her Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","67711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710876","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The MOJ is working with the Government Commercial Function to capture such data going forward as part of our investment in the development of our risk and controls framework.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-03-23T14:18:51.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710876/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710876/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-14","Ministry of Justice: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many contracts procured by her Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710877","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-20","<p>Ministry of Justice records show that there were no secondments to the Department from a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey &amp; Co, (f) Ernst &amp; Young and (g) Bain &amp; Company since July 2016.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-03-20T16:09:38.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710877/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710877/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-14","Ministry of Justice: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff have been seconded to her Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710878","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-22","<p>The interchange of ideas and the critical challenge that those with external perspectives, including consultancies and consultants, can bring to policy and delivery of Government priorities is a critical element for good government.</p><p> </p><p>Short term expertise can inject targeted support at critical points ensuring value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>This department is committed to the benefits that can be brought from the interchange with other sectors, large employers and consultancies.</p><p> </p><p>From departmental records the present number of those on secondment to the department is presented in the table below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>PwC</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Deloitte</p></td><td><p>less than 5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Accenture</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>McKinsey &amp; Co</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ernst and Young</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bain &amp; Company</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-22T11:02:48.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710878/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710878/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-14","Department for Transport: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff have been seconded to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710879","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-22","<p>Department for Transport contractors are required to comply with all legal requirements, including TUPE. My department does not hold central records on application of the legislation at individual contract level.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-22T11:19:35.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710879/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710879/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-14","Department for Transport: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710881","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Department is aware of the fatalities in the Retford area between 2014 – 2016 and recognises that each death by suicide on the railway is one too many. The rail industry has a significant work stream in place to prevent suicide on the network which brings together the Rail Delivery Group, Samaritans, the British Transport Police and the Department in a bid to reduce the risk of suicide on our railways.</p><p> </p><p>Part of Network Rail’s suicide prevention escalation process is to alert local authorities where it is believed a cluster (as defined by Public Health England guidance) of suicides or attempted suicides are taking place. Network Rail is proactive in contacting the relevant local authority to ask about their suicide prevention work and how this can be supported.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail takes preventative measures including fencing on disused platforms, along with signage and training of staff.</p><p> </p><p>In particular high risk areas, they also work with the local community to look for those who are vulnerable to suicide. It is important that the police, the wider rail industry, as well as other appropriate local stakeholders, should be involved in the development and implementation of local authorities suicide prevention plans, particularly in high-risk locations.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-03-21T12:09:32.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710881/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710881/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-14","East Coast Railway Line: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to prevent suicides on the East Coast Main Line through Retford.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","67720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710882","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-22","<p>All contracts have agreed standard terms and conditions and these include obligations related to provision of TUPE. The total number of contracts for the years 12/13, 13/14, and 14/15 is 932.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-22T16:50:10.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710882/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710882/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-14","Department for Work and Pensions: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710883","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-22","<p>The interchange of ideas and the critical challenge that those with external perspectives, including consultancies and consultants, can bring to policy and delivery of Government priorities is a critical element for good government.</p><p> </p><p>We do not record centrally the organisations from which people are seconded into the department. This information, therefore, could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-22T10:51:38.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710883/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710883/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-14","Department for Work and Pensions: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff have been seconded to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710884","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-22","<p>The rule changes proposed in the recent consultation are deregulatory. As a consequence, a Regulatory Triage Assessment dated 2 August 2016 was completed and is publicly available</p><p>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/590721/Land-Registry-Regulatory-Triage-Assessment.docx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/590721/Land-Registry-Regulatory-Triage-Assessment.docx</a>).</p><p> </p><p>A final stage impact assessment will be submitted to the Regulatory Policy Committee in advance of clearance being sought for the rules to be made.</p><p> </p><p>So far as the Rule changes that deal with digital conveyancing are concerned, they are permissive in nature. They would allow, but not force, businesses to use new digital conveyancing and registration services.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-22T15:53:53.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710884/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710884/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Electronic Conveyancing: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the proposals in the Land Registry's consultation on amending the Land Registration Rules Act 2003 relating to large-scale electronic conveyancing on (a) all small and medium-sized conveyancing companies and (b) small and medium-sized conveyancing companies based in rural areas with poor internet coverage.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","67779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710885","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Government announced at Autumn Statement 2016 that it would reform the Land Registry in the public sector. The Government continually reviews all arm’s length bodies and partner organisations to make sure that public services operate efficiently and effectively for customers and the taxpayer.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-22T16:05:44.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710885/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710885/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Land Registry: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government has undertaken an assessment of the potential merits of moving responsibility for the Land Registry to the Department for Communities and Local Government.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","67780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710886","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Payment Systems Regulator is responsible for monitoring compliance with the Interchange Fee Regulation in the UK and for taking enforcement action where appropriate. Government has therefore not made an analysis of the number of companies that do not comply with the Regulation.</p><p> </p><p>The Interchange Fee Regulation (IFR) caps the fees that a merchant acquirer can be charged by a card issuing bank at 0.2% and 0.3% for debit and credit cards respectively. This cost can be passed on to consumers through the practice of surcharging. The Government recently closed a consultation on how the revised Payment Services Directive should be implemented in the UK. One of the provisions in the Directive is a ban on merchants surcharging cards regulated under the IFR.</p><p> </p><p>The interchange fee is part of the merchant service charge that a merchant pays to its bank or merchant acquirer to process its card transactions</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-22T11:31:23.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710886/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710886/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-14","Credit Cards: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) airline and (b) other companies that charge over the 0.3 per cent cap for credit card transactions.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","67778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710887","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has one member of staff on secondment from (b) Deloitte, whose secondment started prior to July 2016 but is on-going. We had a member of staff on secondment from (a) PWC, which started prior to July 2016 and ended in September 2016. There have been no other staff seconded from PWC, Deloitte, Accenture, McKinsey &amp; Co, Ernst and Young or Bain &amp; Company since July 2016.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-21T15:30:08.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710887/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710887/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many staff have been seconded to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710888","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Department does not hold details of the number of contracts covered by TUPE Regulations and information is not held on this matter for the Department’s arms-length bodies.</p><p>Contracts are created using standard terms and conditions which generally contain clauses that relate to TUPE and, amongst other things, place obligations on the supplier to provide information and to cooperate with the Department during any transfer of services.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-21T15:31:16.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710888/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710888/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710889","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Department is currently in transition following the announcement of its formation in July last year and the bringing together of the functions of the Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) along with the business, industrial strategy and innovation functions of the former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS).</p><p>DECC adopted the (real) Living Wage in 1 April 2014. This was not a contractual requirement but achieved by a contract variation negotiated with our facilities management supplier to enable them to pay two of their subcontractors (security and catering service providers) the higher rate of pay to their staff in scope. BIS has no contracts requiring the contractor to pay its employees the real Living Wage. The Department does not hold on information on this matter for the Department’s arms-length bodies.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-21T15:29:25.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710889/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710889/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies require that the contractor pays those of its employees undertaking the work contracted for the real living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710890","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-20","<p>The UK acts in accordance with Common Position 2008/944/CFSP in its application of the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. These Criteria were set out in a written ministerial statement by the former Business Secretary on 25 March 2014 as guidance given under section 9 of the Export Control Act 2002.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-20T14:30:23.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710890/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710890/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Arms Trade: Export Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what basis European Council Common Position 2008/944/CFSP has in UK law.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","67726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710891","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>Following her appointment on 13 July 2016 the Prime Minister established the Department for International Trade (DIT).</p><p> </p><p>The interchange of ideas and the critical challenge that those with external perspectives, including consultancies and consultants, can bring to policy and delivery of Government priorities is a critical element for good government.</p><p> </p><p>Short term expertise can inject targeted support at critical points ensuring value for money for the taxpayer. This department is committed to the benefits that can be brought from the interchange with other sectors, large employers and consultancies.</p><p> </p><p>At present the Department for International Trade has not had any staff seconded from the organisations listed since its formation in July 2016, but will consider secondees in future where appropriate.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T16:30:25.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710891/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710891/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Department for International Trade: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff have been seconded to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710892","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>TUPE regulations have the potential to apply to all contracts where there is a transfer of service from one provider to another. As such all contracts relating to services have the potential to fall within the scope of this legislation. The Department for International Trade was formed in July 2016 and since its creation 1 new contract has been identified may fall within the scope of the legislation.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T14:23:46.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710892/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710892/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Department for International Trade: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710893","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-22","<p>Since its creation in July 2016, no contracts procured by DExEU have been covered by TUPE regulations. <br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-03-22T11:30:40.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710893/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710893/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies are covered by TUPE regulations in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710894","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Government believes that people have the right to a higher wage and not to be punished by higher taxes. As part of this, from April 2016, we introduced a new mandatory National Living Wage (NLW) for workers aged 25 and above, and this will rise to £7.50 an hour in April 2017. We insist that employers pay at least the National Living Wage for workers aged 25 and above and the National Minimum Wage for those under 25. <br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-03-22T11:24:23.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710894/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710894/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies require that the contractor pays those of its employees undertaking the work contracted for the real living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710895","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-22","<p>The department has sourced a large proportion of experienced staff from across Whitehall and a number of secondees from the private sector and the wider public sector. We are not in a position to give a final total for particular groups of staff as recruitment is ongoing and numbers are regularly changing.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-03-22T11:28:02.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710895/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710895/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff have been seconded to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Accenture, (d) McKinsey & Co, (f) Ernst and Young and (g) Bain & Company since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710897","Attorney General","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) is committed to tackling disability hate crime and is prosecuting, and convicting, more defendants for disability hate crimes than ever before. In 2015/16, the CPS completed 941 disability hate crime prosecutions, an increase from 666 the previous year and the conviction rate has remained steady at 75%.</p><p>The CPS delivered mandatory face to face disability hate crime training between September 2015 and January 2016 to support prosecutors to more effectively deal with disability hate crime cases.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-03-20T11:36:07.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710897/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710897/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-03-14","Hate Crime: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent progress has been made in increasing the prosecution rate for disability hate crime offences.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","67906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710898","Attorney General","false","2017-03-21","<p>(a) Government Legal Department: The 330 lawyers in the Litigation Group are at Senior Civil Service, Grade 6 and Grade 7.</p><p>(b) Crown Prosecution Service: The grades of the 12.5 (FTE) members of commercial staff are shown in the below table.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Civil Service Grade</p></td><td><p>CPS Commercial staff @ 31/01/2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>G7</p></td><td><p>2.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SEO</p></td><td><p>4.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HEO</p></td><td><p>3.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>EO</p></td><td><p>1.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>AO</p></td><td><p>0.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>AA</p></td><td><p>2.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>12.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>(c) Serious Fraud Office: The three members of the procurement team are one Grade 6 (who also manages the Facilities Management Team), one Senior Executive Officer and one Higher Executive Officer.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-03-21T13:41:59.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710898/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710898/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-03-14","Attorney General: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Answer of 13 March 2017 to Question 66990, what the pay grades are of the (a) 330 lawyers from the GLD's litigation group, (b) 12.5 full-time equivalent Crown Prosecution Service staff and (c) three Serious Fraud Office staff employed.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","68004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710899","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-20","<p>In accordance with the recommendation in Lord Young's report, a review of central government's approach to implementing the Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012 has been undertaken in preparation for a cross Whitehall paper, with input from a range of external stakeholders invited for their expertise in the field. This forms part of a wider review of the act I announced on 9th February and further details will be announced in due course.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-03-20T15:55:43.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710899/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710899/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-14","Government Departments: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 13 March 2017 to Question 66974, on Government contracts, who the experts on that panel were; for what reasons those experts were chosen to serve on that panel; and how frequently that panel met.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710900","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Government Transformation Strategy, published in February, includes an assessment of how data sharing across Whitehall could be made more efficient. Specific opportunities for improvement identified within the strategy include the development of registers to ensure reference data is easy to maintain and use.</p><p> </p><p>The potential of data sharing to save time and resource in several key areas across Whitehall has been analysed as part of the data sharing measures set out in the Digital Economy Bill. These measures enable easier data sharing to improve the public services and functions we deliver. For example, providing automatic rebates to those in fuel poverty would cost less than £1 per household to deliver, while non-automated methods can cost up to £30 per customer.</p><p> </p><p>Industries outside the public sector will also benefit from cost savings enabled by the Digital Economy Bill: the transformation of data collection practices will lead to reduction, over time, of costs associated with compliance, currently estimated at £24 million annually for UK businesses.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","67911","2017-03-21T11:41:18.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710900/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710900/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-14","Government Departments: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of potential savings arising from increased data sharing across Whitehall.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","67910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710901","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Government Transformation Strategy, published in February, includes an assessment of how data sharing across Whitehall could be made more efficient. Specific opportunities for improvement identified within the strategy include the development of registers to ensure reference data is easy to maintain and use.</p><p> </p><p>The potential of data sharing to save time and resource in several key areas across Whitehall has been analysed as part of the data sharing measures set out in the Digital Economy Bill. These measures enable easier data sharing to improve the public services and functions we deliver. For example, providing automatic rebates to those in fuel poverty would cost less than £1 per household to deliver, while non-automated methods can cost up to £30 per customer.</p><p> </p><p>Industries outside the public sector will also benefit from cost savings enabled by the Digital Economy Bill: the transformation of data collection practices will lead to reduction, over time, of costs associated with compliance, currently estimated at £24 million annually for UK businesses.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","67910","2017-03-21T11:41:18.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710901/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710901/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-14","Government Departments: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent assessment he has made of the efficacy of data sharing across Whitehall.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","67911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710902","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-29","<p>HM Treasury’s Green Book guidance applies to the appraisal of all proposals that require use of public resources or assessment of public value. The Green Book also applies to the appraisal of value in Regulatory Impact Assessments.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS provides specific guidance for Regulatory Impact Assessments, which are mandatory for any measure that has a significant regulatory impact on business and civil society organisations.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-03-29T16:46:49.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710902/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710902/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-14","Government Departments: Impact Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what guidance government departments receive on when they are (a) required and (b) encouraged to conduct an impact assessment.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","67805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710903","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-20","<p>The premiership of the former Prime Minister, the Rt Hon David Cameron.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-20T12:09:06.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710903/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710903/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-14","Cabinet Office: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2017 to Question 67375, on government responses to written questions, what his definition is of the last administration.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","67896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710904","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-20","<p>As I indicated in my previous answer of 14 March (62917), we will provide a definitive answer to the Hon. Member as soon as possible.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-20T12:13:02.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710904/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710904/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-14","Cabinet Office: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2017 to Question 67375, on government responses to written questions, how long he expects that task of manual checking to take.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","67899"
