"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710989","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>This information, on closures, would be held by local authorities and not collected centrally. Under the Zoo Licensing Act 1981, there is no requirement for local authorities to report the closure of a zoo of any size to the Department.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","67815","2017-03-20T16:13:57.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710989/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710989/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Zoos: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether a zoo containing more than 1,000 animals has been closed by a local authority in the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","67816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710990","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>This information, on closures, would be held by local authorities and not collected centrally. Under the Zoo Licensing Act 1981, there is no requirement for local authorities to report the closure of a zoo of any size to the Department.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","67816","2017-03-20T16:13:57.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710990/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710990/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Zoos: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many times zoos have been closed by local authorities in the last 20 years; and for what reasons those zoos were closed.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","67815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710991","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Zoos Expert Committee (ZEC) provides independent, technical advice to the UK Governments on zoo matters. The ZEC keeps the operation and implementation of the zoo licensing system in the UK under review and advises Defra and devolved governments of any legislative or administrative changes that may be required. Membership of the ZEC includes representatives of local authorities who provide ongoing advice on the operation of the Zoo Licensing Act 1981. The ZEC will also, if necessary, seek and receive representations from any local authority with knowledge of enforcing the zoo licensing system. Defra commissioned a study in 2010 to review the effectiveness of local authorities’ implementation of the Zoo Licensing Act 1981. The report was published in 2011 and found no strong evidence of a need for legislative change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following the recent case in Cumbria, Lord Gardiner will be discussing, with ZEC, whether any further steps need to be taken to ensure animal welfare.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","67818","2017-03-20T16:14:36.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710991/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710991/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Zoos: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when her Department last conducted a review of the framework for the statutory regulation of zoos.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","67817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710992","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Zoos Expert Committee (ZEC) provides independent, technical advice to the UK Governments on zoo matters. The ZEC keeps the operation and implementation of the zoo licensing system in the UK under review and advises Defra and devolved governments of any legislative or administrative changes that may be required. Membership of the ZEC includes representatives of local authorities who provide ongoing advice on the operation of the Zoo Licensing Act 1981. The ZEC will also, if necessary, seek and receive representations from any local authority with knowledge of enforcing the zoo licensing system. Defra commissioned a study in 2010 to review the effectiveness of local authorities’ implementation of the Zoo Licensing Act 1981. The report was published in 2011 and found no strong evidence of a need for legislative change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following the recent case in Cumbria, Lord Gardiner will be discussing, with ZEC, whether any further steps need to be taken to ensure animal welfare.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","67817","2017-03-20T16:14:36.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710992/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710992/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Zoos: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent representations her Department has received from local authorities on the effectiveness and scope of current zoo regulations.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","67818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710993","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>1,729 claimants received payments of around £50 million which were made outside the Basic Payment Scheme 2015 window which ran between 1 December 2015 and 30 June 2016. Payments made between January 2016 and June 2016 were paid within the scheme window. That is why the answer to this question is the same as the answer to Question 66880.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-20T17:10:18.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710993/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710993/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 March 2017 to Question 66880, what information her Department holds on the number and value of individual payments which were not paid within the basic payment scheme window since 30 June 2016; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710994","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Royal College of Veterinary Surgeons already has a statutory examination for non-EU registrants whose examinations are not automatically recognised by the College. Applicants must reach level 7 of the International English Language Testing System (IELTS) before applying to sit this exam. Government is currently reviewing the content of the EU Mutual Recognition Directive.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-21T12:20:51.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710994/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710994/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Veterinary Services: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to make the language requirements for non-EU national veterinary surgeons to practice the same as with those which apply to non-UK EU nationals .","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","67918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710995","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-21","<p>We are working closely with local authorities to help them deal with the impacts of ash dieback by supporting them to be prepared and by providing guidance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Infected ash trees can survive dieback for many years, continuing to provide recreational and biodiversity benefits, and could provide a source of disease tolerance in the future. For this very reason we are not encouraging the removal of infected ash unless it poses an immediate health and safety risk.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To ensure that the issue of health and safety is addressed we have convened an ash dieback taskforce with a number of key stakeholders and local authorities. We are working closely with this group to develop action plans for local authorities and supplement existing guidance for landowners, such as that published by the National Tree Safety Group. We will be making the action plans available for all local authorities in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Local action plan work has initially focused on the areas most likely to be affected in the next few years, but we have been working with other areas and held workshops across the country to inform the research, and we will be engaging local authorities in the North West in this work later this year.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-21T16:10:50.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710995/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710995/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Ash Dieback Disease: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to help local authorities in the North West whose area is affected by ash dieback.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","67937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710997","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>The value of any late payment penalties relating to the 2015 Basic Payment Scheme will not be known until Summer 2017, when they are due to be calculated by the European Commission based on the latest payment data from across the UK.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-20T15:55:17.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710997/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710997/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the (a) number and (b) value of EU disallowance penalties incurred for late payments by the Rural Payments Agency of basic payments between 1 December 2015 and 30 June 2016; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710999","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-22","<p>The annual value of the Pillar 1 budget fluctuates with currency movements but the budget for the 2016 scheme year for the UK was circa £2.7bn. It is too early to calculate the equivalent value for the 2019/2020 scheme year.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","67934","2017-03-22T12:47:49.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710999/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/710999/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the financial effect on farming by 2020 if funding currently provided under Pillar 1 of the Common Agricultural Policy is withdrawn when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711000","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>Defra is not undertaking research in this area though we understand that various organizations, such as Building Research Establishment (BRE), Royal Institute of British Architects (RIBA) and the Baca architectural partnership are already engaged in this area.</p><p> </p><p>We are continuing to explore with the industry more widely on how people could be incentivised to take action to manage their flood risk. We recently published the Property Flood Resilience Action Plan. The group has set up task groups in specific areas to examine detailed issues.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-20T10:06:52.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711000/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711000/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Floods: Property Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to help facilitate research into can-float flood resilient buildings for infill development in flood risk zones.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","67955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711002","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The UK has a number of agreements with other countries to facilitate the removal and deportation of those with no right to remain in the UK. The Dublin III Regulation is EU law that enables transfer of asylum seekers to other participating States in Europe who are responsible for examining the claim. The UK participates in 14 EU Readmission Agreements, some of which contain clauses to return third country nationals, meaning individuals who are not a national of that country. Returns to other countries may also be on a case by case basis with the consent of the third country.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-21T14:52:50.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711002/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711002/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with which countries the UK has a Memorandum of Understanding to facilitate enforced deportation to a third country.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","67970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711003","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-20","<p>The British Embassy in Kabul has approximately 160 local staff, many of whom speak Dari or Pashto as their native language. We also have a small number of UK-based roles in Kabul where we train incumbents to speak Dari or Pashto.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","67806","2017-03-20T16:35:08.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711003/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711003/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Pashto and Persian Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many officials in his Department are fluent in (a) Dari and (b) Pashto; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","67810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711004","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-20","<p>Of the approximately 50 staff overseeing major departmental contracts that are delivered in or from the UK for the FCO worldwide, there are currently three Senior Civil Servants.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-20T16:41:57.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711004/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711004/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2017 to Question 64998, at what pay grades the 50 civil servants who oversee major departmental contracts are employed.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711005","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-20","<p>The British Embassy in Kabul has approximately 160 local staff, many of whom speak Dari or Pashto as their native language. We also have a small number of UK-based roles in Kabul where we train incumbents to speak Dari or Pashto.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","67810","2017-03-20T16:35:08.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711005/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711005/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","Afghanistan: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK diplomats and members of staff at the UK embassy in Kabul are fluent in (a) Dari and (b) Pashto; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","67806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711006","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-20","<p>We are delighted to be hosting the 2018 Western Balkans Summit, as part of our strong and enduring commitment to the Western Balkans. No decision has yet been taken on where in the UK the Summit will be held.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-20T16:44:14.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711006/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711006/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","Balkans: EU Enlargement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what consideration has been given to the geographical location of the Western Balkans summit in 2018.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","67790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711007","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The FCO awarded 20 major contracts over the last 3 year period. Major contracts are defined as those with a whole life cost over £15m. The FCO does not centrally hold data about all contracts and to provide this information would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-21T16:44:42.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711007/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711007/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2017 to Question 64998, if he will estimate the proportion of contracts awarded to external providers that are defined as major departmental contracts.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711008","Department for Education","false","2017-03-21","<p>The statutory responsibility for transport to education and training for children of compulsory school age and for 16 to 19 year olds rests with local authorities, enabling them to make decisions which best match local needs and circumstances.</p><p>Local authorities are required to consult a range of stakeholders including schools and colleges about their post-16 transport policies. When developing transport policies for children of compulsory school age statutory guidance strongly encourages local authorities to consult.</p><p>Local authorities publish transport policies for school age children and post-16 young people on their websites. The department does not assess these to determine the extent to which local authorities meet these expectations for consultation. Links to post-16 transport policies can be found at www.gov.uk/subsidised-college-transport-16-19.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-21T14:00:13.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711008/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711008/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-14","Schools: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish a list of school transport plans with no mechanism for engaging schools and colleges as active stakeholders.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","67935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711009","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Government is carefully considering the recommendations in the Accelerated Access Review with its key partners and will provide a formal response shortly.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T16:50:55.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711009/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711009/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Innovative Medicines and Medical Technology Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to publish the Government's response to the accelerated access review.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","67897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711011","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has advised that it has published seven technology appraisals on products that have received a positive scientific opinion through the Early Access to Medicines Scheme. Information on NICE’s recommendations for each appraisal is shown in the attached table.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T17:37:07.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711011/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711011/answer","PQ67898 attached table.docx","PQ67898 attached table.docx","PQ67898 attached table","PQ67898 attached table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711011/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Drugs: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many technology appraisals NICE has undertaken for medicines which have successfully passed through the Early Access to Medicines Scheme; and what the NICE recommendation was for each of those appraisals.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","67898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711012","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The £127 million is a permanent uplift to the NHS England mandate. NHS England has proposed to increase clinical commissioning group (CCGs) budgets to reflect these cost pressures in 2016/17 and 2017/18. Thereafter, and in common with all other elements of funding, NHS England is proposing to include this in the general funding allocation for CCGs as it does not generally allocate funding on the basis of specific costs, for example property costs.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-22T13:41:18.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711012/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711012/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Clinical commissioning groups: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 24 February 2017 to Question 63650, on clinical commissioning groups: buildings, whether the additional £127 million to fund the increase in costs is for 2016-17 only.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","67880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711013","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Government's Violence against Women and Girls Strategy (VAWG) published in March 2016 committed increased funding of £80 million for VAWG services. A further £20 million was announced in the March 2017 Budget to support organisations that tackle domestic violence and abuse and work is ongoing to integrate this with the already announced funding.</p><p> </p><p>We have provided approximately £2 million of central funding for VAWG services in Yorkshire which has supported refuge provision, Independent Domestic Violence Advisers, Independent Sexual Violence Advisers and Rape Support Centres.</p><p> </p><p>We have also set out a clear blueprint for local action though our new National Statement of Expectations (NSE) and Commissioning Toolkit, which is available to local commissioning bodies and groups. Our move to support through the VAWG Service Transformation Fund will encourage better collaboration and new, joined-up approaches between local commissioners, and with specialist VAWG service providers. This will help promote better collaboration and joint leadership, encourage new approaches incorporating early intervention, and establish and embed the best ways to help victims, survivors and their families.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we will shortly be announcing successful bids in our three year £15 million VAWG Service Transformation Fund.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-03-21T15:16:47.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711013/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711013/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Crimes of Violence: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to paragraph 5.13 of the Spring Budget 2017, what estimate she has made of how much of £100 million funding for implementing the Government's Ending Violence Against Women and Girls Strategy will be allocated to (a) Leeds East constituency, (b) Leeds and (c) Yorkshire.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","67834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711014","Department of Health","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Department has not yet determined which Sustainability and Transformation Plan areas will receive the additional funding allocated in the Spring Budget.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-21T10:27:26.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711014/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711014/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Health Services: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 5.8 of the Spring Budget 2017, what estimate he has made of how much of £325 million funding for local sustainability and transformation plans will be allocated to (a) Leeds East constituency, (b) Leeds and (c) Yorkshire.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","67832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711015","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T09:22:52.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711015/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711015/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Bereavement Counselling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS spent in bereavement services in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","67872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711016","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>Further detail on the changes to services that will take place will be outlined in the NHS Delivery Plan.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-20T16:17:22.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711016/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711016/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what changes to services will take place as a result of the standardisation of walk-in centres, minor injury units and urgent care centres by NHS England.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","67803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711017","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has advised that it takes the opinion provided by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency into account, where it is considered relevant to its recommendations. NICE offers companies the opportunity to meet with NICE and NHS England to discuss feasibility/applicability of proposed plans to collect data during the Early Access to Medicines Scheme period which could inform a NICE evaluation. NICE endeavours to schedule these topics into its work programme as soon as possible, so that it can produce timely guidance.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T16:53:19.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711017/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711017/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Drugs: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what account NICE takes of the fact that medicines have successfully passed through the Early Access to Medicines Scheme due to high unmet medical needs when undertaking technology appraisals.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","67809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711018","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>NHS England and Health Education England are working closely with providers and professional bodies to develop the workforce further within Integrated Urgent Care and National Health Service 111 services through the Workforce Development Programme.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-20T13:24:09.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711018/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711018/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","NHS 111: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what changes will be made to the workforce of NHS 111 to support on-site assessment in care homes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","67808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711019","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>The numbers of staff required for streaming services will be locally determined by health systems and based on the specific streaming model they employ, the staff mix local system leaders determine is required, and the demand profile in the local area.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-20T12:46:17.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711019/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711019/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Accident and Emergency Departments: General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many GPs will be employed in staffing the comprehensive front door streaming model at accident and emergency departments from October 2017; and what assessment he has made of the capacity of the GP workforce to meet that demand.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","67813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711020","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-20","<p>On 15 February 2017, the Government announced that the delivery of public health services will be funded through retained business rates; replacing the Public Health Grant. The Government’s intention is to implement the 100 per cent business rates retention system from 1 April 2019.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-20T12:44:14.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711020/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711020/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-14","Non-domestic Rates: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, by what date he plans for public health to be fully funded from local authority business rate retention.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","67814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711021","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>Information on products that have received marketing authorisation and orphan designation since 2013 is contained in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>Since April 2013 there have been 48 drugs designated as orphan against 62 indications. Of these indications, 28 are routinely commissioned, of which:</p><p> </p><p>- eight are recommended in National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) technology appraisal guidance;</p><p>- three are recommended in NICE Highly Specialised Technologies guidance;</p><p>- 11 are commissioned under an NHS England Policy; and</p><p>- six are available through the Cancer Drugs Fund.</p><p> </p><p>26 indications are not currently routinely commissioned. Of these:</p><p> </p><p>- 15 are being assessed through NICE’s technology appraisal or highly specialised technologies work programmes;</p><p>- four are on NHS England’s programme;</p><p>- three are not launched in the United Kingdom; and</p><p>- four are launched in the UK, but not currently being considered for routine funding.</p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups are responsible for one of the remaining eight products and information is not held centrally on their availability. Information is not available on the remainder of products.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","67798","2017-03-20T17:02:26.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711021/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711021/answer","PQ67797 attached table.xlsx","PQ67797 attached table.xlsx","PQ67797 attached table","PQ67797 attached table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711021/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Chronic Illnesses: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what products for rare and ultra-rare disease treatment have received European Medicines Agency marketing authorisation and orphan designation since 2013; and which of those products is routinely available to patients in England.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","67797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711022","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>The provision of cough assist machines is a matter for local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs). CCGs have the independence and autonomy to make commissioning decisions for local populations, taking into account the available evidence and individual circumstances as appropriate.</p><p>Currently, the evidence base to support the routine use of cough assist machines in muscle-wasting conditions is not well established. NHS England worked with Muscular Dystrophy UK through its Bridging the Gap project to address areas of concern raised by patients and their representatives, one of which was the provision of cough assist machines. Through this work, a number of CGGs developed commissioning policies which set out the circumstances in which to consider these devices. In addition, in February 2016 the National institute for Health and Care Excellence published new guidance on the assessment and management of motor neurone disease, recommending that cough assist machines should be considered if assisted breath stacking is not effective, and/or during a respiratory tract infection.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-20T16:41:19.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711022/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711022/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Neuromuscular Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to encourage clinical commissioning groups to increase access to cough-assist machines for people with muscle-wasting conditions, such as muscular dystrophy.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","67796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711023","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>As part of NHS England’s Quality Assurance programme, an annual assessment is conducted for all specialised services. This commences with a provider self-declaration against a range of key requirements drawn from the service specification. The provider declaration is then considered alongside a range of other quality data such as information derived from the specialised services quality dashboards and from local commissioners who meet routinely with providers.</p><p> </p><p>This process, undertaken in full for the first time in 2016/17, has provided NHS England with a strengthened ability to assess provider compliance. Where non-compliance is identified, local commissioners have assessed what areas are affected, and whether the issue is amenable to a short term action plan which the provider develops and implements with oversight from local commissioners. Where the non-compliance is not considered to be amenable to a short term action plan, commissioner action is required to ensure availability of a compliant service for the future.</p><p> </p><p>The compliance level for the specialised neurology services specification is very high with only a small number of services requiring a provider action plan or commissioner action.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-20T16:43:04.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711023/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711023/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Neuromuscular Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of neuroscience centres in meeting NHS England service specifications of neurological care.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","67795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711024","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>Information on products that have received marketing authorisation and orphan designation since 2013 is contained in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>Since April 2013 there have been 48 drugs designated as orphan against 62 indications. Of these indications, 28 are routinely commissioned, of which:</p><p> </p><p>- eight are recommended in National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) technology appraisal guidance;</p><p>- three are recommended in NICE Highly Specialised Technologies guidance;</p><p>- 11 are commissioned under an NHS England Policy; and</p><p>- six are available through the Cancer Drugs Fund.</p><p> </p><p>26 indications are not currently routinely commissioned. Of these:</p><p> </p><p>- 15 are being assessed through NICE’s technology appraisal or highly specialised technologies work programmes;</p><p>- four are on NHS England’s programme;</p><p>- three are not launched in the United Kingdom; and</p><p>- four are launched in the UK, but not currently being considered for routine funding.</p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups are responsible for one of the remaining eight products and information is not held centrally on their availability. Information is not available on the remainder of products.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","67797","2017-03-20T17:02:26.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711024/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711024/answer","PQ67797 attached table.xlsx","PQ67797 attached table.xlsx","PQ67797 attached table","PQ67797 attached table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711024/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Medical Treatments: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 15 December 2016 to Question 56707, on diseases, how many of the 46 products that had received European Medicines Agency marketing authorisation and orphan designation since 2013 are undergoing assessment by NICE or NHS England; how many of those products are routinely commissioned in England; how many of those products received a positive evaluation through NICE's technology appraisal system; and how many of the six products selected for the highly specialised technologies programme received a positive evaluation.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","67798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711025","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>NHS England intends to publish a full response on behalf of all of the National Health Service arm’s length bodies to the report by the Commission on Acute Psychiatric Care shortly.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T17:03:37.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711025/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711025/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Mental Health Services: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his policy is on recommendation 9 of the report Old Problems, New Solutions: Improving Acute Psychiatric Care for Adults in England, published by the Commission on Acute Psychiatric Care in February 2016, to pilot a new patients and carers race equality standard.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","67799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711026","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Department will manage the approval of funding to accident and emergency (A&amp;E) departments based on recommendations from NHS England and NHS Improvement, according to the merit of individual bids made and the impact they will have on managing A&amp;E pressures.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-22T16:12:43.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711026/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711026/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Accident and Emergency Departments: Leeds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 5.7 of the Spring Budget 2017, what estimate he has made of how much of the £100 million funding for capital investment in accident and emergency departments in 2017-18 will be allocated to (a) Leeds General Infirmary and (b) St James' Hospital, Leeds.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","67837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711027","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Department published the allocations for the additional funding for adult social care announced at the Spring Budget 2017 online on 9 March, together with an Explanatory Note.</p><p>This is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-allocations-of-the-additional-funding-for-adult-social-care" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-allocations-of-the-additional-funding-for-adult-social-care</a>.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-20T12:41:20.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711027/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711027/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-14","Social Services: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to page 3 of the Spring Budget 2017, how much of the additional £2 billion of additional social care funding he plans to allocate to Warrington.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","67966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711028","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Government’s mandate to NHS England for 2017-18 was published and laid before Parliament on 20 March 2017, ahead of coming into force on 1 April 2017.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-22T17:04:17.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711028/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711028/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to publish the Mandate to NHS England as required under section 13A(7) of the National Health Service Act 2006","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","67932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711029","Department of Health","false","2017-03-21","<p>NHS England hold the contract with Capita Business Services Ltd for primary care support services. No estimate has been made of the cost to the National Health Service of dealing with the missed requirements of Capita in relation to the contract, but NHS England inform us that they continue to work with Capita to mitigate implications for the service and rectify any issues to ensure that services are at an acceptable and sustainable standard.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-21T10:28:55.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711029/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711029/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Capita: Primary Health Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the cost to the NHS of dealing with the missed requirements of Capita in relation to the contract for the management of primary care support services.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","67933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711031","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Department does not hold figures on this. However, the British Heart Foundation was awarded £1 million by the Department in both 2015/16 and 2016/17 to invest in public access defibrillators.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England’s National Clinical Director for Cardiovascular Disease Prevention is supporting the British Heart Foundation in its work to identify the location of public access defibrillators. The aim is to establish a national database and to make this available to ambulance services.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-22T17:05:29.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711031/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711031/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Defibrillators: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate has been made of the number of public-access defibrillators in (a) Pendle, (b) Lancashire and (c) the North West.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","67939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711032","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Department is developing plans to establish a new National Health Service property organisation, in response to early recommendations made by Sir Robert Naylor’s ongoing review of the NHS estate. We are committed to ensuring that the new organisation fully supports and reflects the needs and priorities of the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>Further details on the proposed new organisation are currently being developed, and these details will be set out in a business case to Department of Health Ministers in due course.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-22T13:42:46.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711032/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711032/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","NHS Property Services: Community Health Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 24 February 2017 to Question 63652, on NHS Property Services Communities Health Partnerships, whether a business case was prepared to support the plans to establish a new NHS property organisation.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","67994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711033","Department of Health","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme enables over 900,000 people a year to access psychological therapy. In 2017/18 part of the Quality Premium (a financial incentive) for clinical commissioning groups is aimed at improving outcomes from Improving Access to Psychological Therapies services for people from black and minority ethnic groups.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-21T10:04:17.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711033/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711033/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Health Services: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to extend counselling opportunities for BME groups in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","67919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711034","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>We are providing the seven worst affected trusts with Private Finance Initiative (PFI) schemes, access to a £1.5 billion support fund over a period of 25 years; funding started from 2013-14.</p><p> </p><p>One of the first things this Government did in 2010 was to launch a review of the previous Government’s PFIs and begin an initiative to extract savings and better value for money at all the PFI contracts they had signed and are now open. In 2014 it was reported that trusts had negotiated validated savings worth over £250 million on their contracts. This savings work is ongoing, with Departmental officials helping local trusts as required.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-22T16:18:01.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711034/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711034/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","NHS Trusts: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to assist hospital trusts to reduce or restructure costs borne as a result of private finance initiatives.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","67920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711035","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Department will manage the approval of funding to accident and emergency (A&amp;E) departments based on recommendations from NHS England and NHS Improvement, according to the merit of individual bids according to the impact they will have on managing A&amp;E pressures. This may include, for example, bids from trusts to provide additional permanent or temporary buildings and/or better use of existing space to allow general practitioners to locate next to A&amp;Es. The allocations for successful bids will be agreed in the next five weeks.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-22T16:20:29.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711035/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711035/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Accident and Emergency Departments: GP Surgeries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what criteria he plans to use to allocate the funds announced in the Spring Budget 2017 for GP surgery co-location in hospital accident and emergency departments.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","67990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711036","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>The data is not collected centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T16:57:06.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711036/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711036/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many non-fatal suicide attempts there were in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","67997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711037","Department of Health","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Department does not directly invest in public information campaigns on suicide prevention.</p><p>Public Health England raises awareness of suicide prevention and provides guidance to local authorities and the National Health Service on various topics, for example mental health in Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender community.</p><p>Addressing the stigma that surrounds mental health, including suicide and self-harm is a priority. We provided additional investment of £12.5 million for the next phase of Time to Change up to 2020 to address mental health stigma. Time to Change recently launched the ‘In your corner’ social marketing campaign to encourage men to talk about mental health which we know can be a significant barrier in terms of preventing suicide in this group.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-20T17:31:28.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711037/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711037/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding his Department allocated to public information campaigns on suicide prevention in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","67998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711038","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>From 1 April 2016, the NHS Mandate required all general practitioner (GP) practices to offer patients online access to their medical record which includes items such as allergies, adverse reactions, medications, test results, problems and diagnoses and immunisations. Approximately 95% of GPs are able to offer this service to patients subject to appropriate safeguards to ensure compliance with information governance legislation.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-22T17:05:00.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711038/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711038/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Medical Records: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects patients to be able to access their own full medical records online.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","67909"
