"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711118","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-20","<p>The two tables below give statistics on the number of people receiving a mobility award with main disabling condition multiple sclerosis who scored b on Activity 11 (mobility activity 1) of their assessment for Personal Independence payment (PIP) for both new claimants and DLA reassessments.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 – Number of new claimants each calendar year receiving a mobility award that scored b on Activity 11 of their PIP assessment</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>New claims</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016 (to 30<sup>th</sup> September)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number scoring b on Activity 11</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>560</p></td><td><p>240</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Table 2 – Number of DLA reassessment claimants each calendar year receiving a mobility award that scored b on Activity 11 of their PIP assessment</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>DLA Reassessments</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016 (to 30<sup>th</sup> September)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number scoring b on Activity 11</p></td><td><p>110</p></td><td><p>180</p></td><td><p>380</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-20T15:26:57.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711118/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711118/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-14","Personal Independence Payment: Multiple Sclerosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the mobility activity 1 of the personal independence payment assessment, how many people with multiple sclerosis who received a mobility award scored points on descriptor b for (a) new claims and (b) disability living allowance reassessments in each year before October 2016.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","67972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711119","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-20","<p>A person who has been assessed for either Employment Support Allowance or Personal Independence Payment can ask to see a copy of their assessment report at any time after its completion. They can do this by telephone, in writing or in person.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-20T17:27:33.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711119/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711119/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-14","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a person who has been assessed for employment and support allowance or personal independent payments is entitled to a copy of the computer file report created by the HCP during their assessment process.","false","Biography information for Dr James Davies","Vale of Clwyd","Dr James Davies","67987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711120","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-22","<p>Claimants are encouraged to provide all evidence they have that is relevant to their case at the outset of their claim, including evidence from their GP or other professionals, such as support workers, carers and community mental health nurses, to ensure advice provided to Decision Makers is of a suitable quality to support a good standard of decision making.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper we are looking at ways to simplify and streamline benefit assessments, including our use of digital services and our ability to use and share appropriate data.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-22T12:57:01.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711120/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711120/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-14","Social Security Benefits: Medical Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect full online medical record access for patients will have on the efficiency of processing employment and support allowance and personal independence payments applications.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","67905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711121","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-22","<p>DWP offers jobseekers a comprehensive range of support to best meet the needs of the jobseeker and the local labour market.</p><p> </p><p>If Jobcentre Plus considers it appropriate, they will refer a jobseeker to a charity, a voluntary organisation or any other body that provides support.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-22T13:12:51.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711121/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711121/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-14","Unemployed People: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what further steps he plans to take to encourage Jobcentre Plus to refer jobseekers to local charity and voluntary groups which offer advice and support to help those seeking a job.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","67984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711122","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-22","<p>The numbers of goods vehicles licensed for use on UK roads, using petrol, diesel and other fuels as at 30 September 2016 are shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Goods vehicles licensed for use on UK roads, as at 30 September 2016</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="4"><p>Reported propulsion type</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Vehicle body type</p></td><td><p>Petrol</p></td><td><p>Diesel</p></td><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Heavy Goods Vehicles</p></td><td><p>2,124</p></td><td><p>514,897</p></td><td><p>868</p></td><td><p>517,889</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Light Goods Vehicles</p></td><td><p>137,535</p></td><td><p>3,741,887</p></td><td><p>14,185</p></td><td><p>3,893,607</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Notes </strong></p><p>DfT statistics based on DVLA registration data</p><p>Figures are for all licensed vehicles with a 'goods' body type</p><p>Heavy goods = gross weight over 3.5 tonnes</p><p>Vehicles converted from petrol or diesel may be under-recorded</p><p>Other propulsion types include hybrids, electric, gas, dual fuels etc.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-22T11:47:25.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711122/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711122/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-14","Large Goods Vehicles: Alternative Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate he has made of the number of road haulage vehicles using fuels other than petrol or diesel.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","67921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711123","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>No decisions have yet been taken on who will represent the UK at the High-Level UN Conference to support implementation of Sustainable Development Goal 14.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-20T10:25:47.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711123/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711123/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Marine Environment: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which Ministers of her Department will be representing the UK at the High-Level UN Conference to Support the Implementation of Sustainable Development Goal 14 in New York on 5 to 9 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","67962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711124","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>Working with the European Union and other Member States we will use this conference to reiterate our commitment to deliver healthy and productive oceans. To achieve this we will press for continued collaboration through the use of existing regional organisations, such as Regional Seas Conventions and Regional Fisheries Management Organisations. We will also aim to secure progress on marine pollution (including marine litter), implementation of the Paris Agreement on climate change, and on a new internationally legally binding instrument under the United Nation Convention on the Law of the Sea.</p><p> </p><p>This will cover measures such as area based management tools (including marine protected areas), environmental impact assessments, capacity building and the transfer of marine technology, and marine genetic resources including questions on the sharing of benefits.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-20T10:23:18.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711124/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711124/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Marine Environment: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what actions she plans to recommend to the High-Level UN Conference to Support the Implementation of Sustainable Development Goal 14 in New York on 5 to 9 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","67963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711125","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>In England and Wales, the following offshore wind projects have development consent and capacities equal or higher than one gigawatt: Dogger Bank Creyke Beck A (1.2GW), Dogger Bank Creyke Beck B (1.2GW), Dogger Bank Teeside A (1.2GW), Dogger Bank Teeside B (1.2GW), Hornsea One (1.2GW), Hornsea Two (1.8GW) and Triton Knoll (1.2GW).</p><p>Hornsea One is currently under construction with target commissioning dates of 31 March 2019, 31 March 2020 and 31 March 2021 for its three phases. Completion dates for the other projects listed above are not known.</p><p>In Scotland, the Moray Firth offshore wind project has consent for 1.116GW. The completion date for this project is not known.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T11:08:07.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711125/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711125/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711125/answer/previousversion/41209","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Renewable Energy: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the completion dates for renewable energy projects across the UK for which (a) planning permission has been approved and (b) the installed capacity is to be equal to or above one gigawatt; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711126","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>We have received representations from the French Government to join a coalition to build a political impetus towards the elimination of single-use plastic bags. The associated declaration makes clear that this goal can be achieved through a variety of measures. Our 5p charge on single use carrier bags is a good example of how we are contributing towards a reduction in the use of single-use plastic bags.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-20T09:50:35.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711126/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711126/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Plastic Bags","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations she has received on the merits of banning all plastic bags in pursuit of achieving the UN Sustainable Development Goal 14 on conservation and sustainable use of the marine environment.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","67964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711127","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Department has not issued any guidance to Ofgem or National Grid on the specific issue of retrospective changes. It is for Ofgem and National Grid to consider the appropriateness of any changes they may wish to make, within the legal framework set by the Government.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-23T11:55:18.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711127/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711127/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Natural Gas: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what guidance his Department issues to (a) National Grid and (b) Ofgem on the frequency of use of retrospective changes to the energy from the gas market.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","67942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711128","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Productivity Leadership Group (PLG) has not received any Government funding. The PLG did received limited ‘in-kind’ support from Government through a short-term staff secondment to help develop a free online productivity benchmarking tool for business.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-03-20T16:24:44.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711128/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711128/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Productivity Leadership Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much Government funding the productivity leadership group has received.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","67967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711129","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Local Growth Fund is awarded to Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs), who prioritise projects for funding in accordance with their local assurance frameworks.</p><p>The London LEP (London Economic Action Partnership) has prioritised the following projects in Newham for receipt of Local Growth Fund:</p><p>The first is the renovation of the Carlsberg-Tetley building (£459,145). 50,000sqft of former brewery office space will be renovated to become a creative workspace. The space will be run by the Mill Co Project, a social enterprise which provide a range of affordable workspaces for creative practitioners in East London.</p><p>The second is the renovation of the former North Woolwich Station Building (£647,000). This Grade II listed former station will be renovated to become an artists’ workspace. In addition, GLA money will restore almost 8000sqm of derelict track land to the rear of the station as a publically accessible green space. The space will include a substantial new community space, and additional artist studio cabins, with construction being undertaken via a readiness to work programme that will provide training for local young people.</p><p>In addition, there is a pan-London Digital Talent Programme (£5m) with outcomes expected to be delivered in east London. Its main aim is to improve London’s advanced digital skills, support 15 -24 year olds and larger numbers of young women, BAME and disadvantaged young Londoners into digital/tech careers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-20T17:00:22.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711129/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711129/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Local Growth Deals: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of the amount disbursed from the £12 billion Local Growth Fund has been allocated to the London Borough of Newham since that fund was opened.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","68001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711130","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Government is currently developing a report outlining the UK’s contribution to delivering the Goals domestically and internationally. The report will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-20T15:24:09.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711130/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711130/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","Marine Environment: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government has taken towards achieving the UN Sustainable Development Goal 14 on conservation and sustainable use of the marine environment since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","67960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711131","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>The EU 2020 renewable energy target requires the UK to achieve 15% of final energy consumption from renewables in electricity generation, heating and transport by 2020.</p><p>We are currently progressing in line with the trajectory set out in the Renewable Energy Directive, having met the Directive’s interim targets for 2011/12 and 2013/14.</p><p>The latest progress report can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493857/3RD_UK_PROGRESS_REPORT_ON_RENEWABLE_ENERGY.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493857/3RD_UK_PROGRESS_REPORT_ON_RENEWABLE_ENERGY.pdf</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T14:18:58.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711131/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711131/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711131/answer/previousversion/41212","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the total proportion of UK energy supply which will come from renewable sources in each of the next 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711132","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold prices on electricity exports over interconnectors. This is commercial information held by market participants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T14:15:24.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711132/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711132/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711132/answer/previousversion/41202","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Electricity: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the average price of electricity exported from the UK through interconnectors was in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","67874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711133","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government routinely publishes total export figures from interconnectors in the annual Digest of UK Energy Statistics (DUKES), and the quarterly National Statistics Energy Trends data. The next Digest is due to be published on 27 July 2017, and provisional 2016 data will feature in the next Energy Trends report due for publication on 30 March.</p><p> </p><p>The latest available 12 month period of data spans Q4 2015 to Q3 2016 and shows a total export of 1,255GWh.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T14:07:58.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711133/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711133/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711133/answer/previousversion/41204","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Electricity: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much electricity was exported from the UK through interconnectors in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","67875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711134","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government does not hold prices on electricity imports over interconnectors. This is commercial information held by market participants.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T14:18:50.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711134/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711134/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711134/answer/previousversion/41206","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Electricity: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the average price of electricity imported into the UK through interconnectors was in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","67876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711135","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Government routinely publishes total import figures from interconnectors in the annual Digest of UK Energy Statistics (DUKES), and the quarterly National Statistics Energy Trends data. The next Digest is due to be published on 27 July 2017, and provisional 2016 data will feature in the next Energy Trends report due for publication on 30 March.</p><p> </p><p>The latest available 12 month period of data spans Q4 2015 to Q3 2016 shows a total import of 21,986GWh.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T14:00:32.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711135/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711135/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711135/answer/previousversion/41205","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Electricity: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much electricity was imported into the UK through interconnectors in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","67877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711136","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Low Pay Commission recommended that the Government consider the case for requiring employers to provide more information on hours worked in workers’ payslips. The Government is currently engaging with stakeholders to better understand this proposal, and will consider the recommendation in the light of this.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-21T11:40:16.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711136/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711136/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 10 March 2017 to Question 66151, on pay, what assessment his Department has made of the merits of providing assistance to workers who are unable to determine whether they have been paid the national minimum wage or national living wage as a result of their pay slips lacking in transparency.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","67782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711137","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-20","<p>There is considerable uncertainty in the costs, timing and the duration of decommissioning activity in the UK. The estimated Exchequer cost of the decommissioning of North Sea oil and gas infrastructure over the period 2015 to 2041 is £16 billion (nominal), as presented in Section 8.3 of HM Revenue and Customs’ annual report and accounts 2014-15:</p><p> </p><p>www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-20T11:38:58.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711137/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711137/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-14","Offshore Fixed Structures: North Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of decommissioning north sea oil and gas platforms over the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711138","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-23","<p>The EU 2020 renewable energy target requires the UK to achieve 15% of final energy consumption from renewables in electricity generation, heating and transport by 2020.</p><p>We are currently progressing in line with the trajectory set out in the Renewable Energy Directive, having met the Directive’s interim targets for 2011/12 and 2013/14.</p><p>Government has confirmed spending on the Renewable Heat Incentive scheme will rise from £430 million in 2015/16 to £1.15 billion in 2020/21, and has consulted on proposals to increase the supply of sustainable biofuels under the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-23T11:44:58.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711138/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711138/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Renewable Energy: Heating and Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the percentage of renewable energy as a percentage of total energy used in the (a) transport and (b) heat sectors in each of the next 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711139","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Capacity Market provides reliable capacity, including gas plant, with secure revenues in return for keeping themselves available when needed. Recent auction outcomes demonstrate the Capacity Market provides the necessary financial incentives to ensure new gas plant are brought forward as and when needed, with up to 1.2GW of new small scale gas winning agreements in 2016 alone.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-23T11:43:19.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711139/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711139/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","National Grid: Natural Gas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with the National Grid on support for small-scale gas energy suppliers to remain in the market.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","67946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711140","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>The average base load wholesale price of electricity in the day-ahead market for the period January to November 2016 was £42 per megawatt-hour*.</p><p> </p><p>*Source: Ofgem electricity prices, <a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/chart/electricity-prices-day-ahead-baseload-contracts-monthly-average-gb" target="_blank">https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/chart/electricity-prices-day-ahead-baseload-contracts-monthly-average-gb</a></p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T14:12:19.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711140/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711140/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711140/answer/previousversion/41208","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-14","Electricity: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the average wholesale price of electricity was in 2016.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","67903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711141","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>Until the UK leaves the EU, we will remain subject to EU trade and investment agreements and policy, including the environmental provisions within trade agreements. The UK has long supported the promotion of our values globally and this will continue as we leave the EU. In addition, the UK is party to around 30 international environmental agreements and treaties in its own right and will continue to be bound by the obligations they contain. We also continue to support the EGA (Environmental Goods Agreement) which is being negotiated through the WTO, and hope that a successful conclusion to negotiations can be achieved as soon as possible.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T14:20:25.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711141/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711141/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Trade Agreements: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what his policy is of the inclusion of environmental goods and services in future trade agreements.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","67783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711142","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Investment Court System (ICS) proposed by the European Commission represents a shift from the existing framework of dispute resolution, and we shall want to consider how it operates once it is implemented, to see if it delivers fairer outcomes, more quickly and at less financial cost than the current framework.</p><p>As the UK develops an independent trade and investment policy, we shall be considering our approach to investment protection, including investor-state dispute resolution, for which the ICS is one model.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T14:17:17.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711142/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711142/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Trade Agreements: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the Investment Court System; what the Government's policy is on that system; and what plans the UK has to promote that system to other countries as part of future trade agreements.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","67784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711143","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Government is working to deliver the best outcomes for the UK. We are exploring a range of options to maximise the opportunities for the UK’s future trade relations and will seek the best possible outcome for the UK as a whole.</p><p>As part of plans for EU exit, we will consider carefully how best to maintain our ability to share, receive and protect EU data with other EU member states.</p><p>Similarly, we will consider how to retain existing rights and obligations to foster transatlantic trade in digital information, products and services across sectors.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T14:15:47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711143/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711143/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Trade Agreements: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he plans to include cross-border data flows in a future trade agreement with (a) the US and (b) the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","67785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711144","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Government believes that people have the right to a higher wage and not to be punished by higher taxes. As part of this, from April 2016, we introduced a new mandatory National Living Wage (NLW) for workers aged 25 and above, and this will rise to £7.50 an hour in April 2017. We insist that employers pay at least the National Minimum Wage.</p><p>The use of the Living Wage as specified by the Living Wage Foundation is not information actively monitored by the Department. This information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T14:26:52.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711144/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711144/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Department for International Trade: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many contracts procured by his Department and its arms-length bodies require that the contractor pays those of its employees undertaking the work contracted for the real living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","67773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711145","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) has 24 civil servants in the dedicated Commercial function which from SCS to AO and includes 2 fast streamers.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T14:05:08.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711145/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711145/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Department for International Trade: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March 2017 to Question 65002, what the pay grade is of the 24 civil servants if his Department employed in the commercial function team.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","68003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711146","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>The value of UK Direct Investment Stock in Poland in each of the last four years is given in the table attached.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T14:12:45.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711146/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711146/answer","07510 table.docx","07510 table.docx","Attached Table","Attached Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711146/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Overseas Investment: Poland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the total British foreign direct investment in Poland was in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","67985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711147","Department for Education","false","2017-03-22","<p>As part of our preparations for exiting the European Union (EU), the Department for Education, along with all Government Departments, is assessing the impact of EU funds and programmes. The replacement of EU funds following the guarantee period will be based on UK strategic priorities and decisions will be taken in light of other domestic spending priorities.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-22T16:33:04.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711147/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711147/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-14","Children: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what impact assessment has been made of the changes in EU funds to ensure that children accessing services currently funded by the EU will not be disadvantaged by the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","67891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711148","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-22","<p>With regard to restricting financial cost relief for landlords, it is estimated that only 1 in 5 landlords will pay more tax as a result of this measure. Given that only a small proportion of the housing market is affected by this change, the Government does not expect it to have a large impact on rent levels.</p><p> </p><p>Landlords are required to maintain their properties to a legal minimum standard. The reform to the wear and tear allowance means that all landlords will now be able to offset the costs of replacing furnishings in their properties removing the previous disincentive to do so.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-22T14:21:29.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711148/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711148/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-14","Tenants: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the tenant tax on private landlords in terms of (a) rental income and (b) property standards.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","67852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711152","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Government plans to make an announcement on this matter in due course.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-03-28T16:17:36.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711152/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711152/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-14","Government Art Collection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Government Art Collection is planning to open a gallery in central London; if so, what is the projected annual cost, and when it will open; and whether they held discussions on locating the gallery outside London prior to making that decision.","false","Biography information for Lord Freyberg",,"Lord Freyberg","HL6040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711153","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>The number of young people who left local authority care in each of the last 10 years, is provided in the table attached.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, the Department for Communities and Local Government issued statutory guidance for local authorities on social housing allocations. The guidance makes clear that those leaving care should be treated as a priority group for social housing. In addition, care leavers aged 18-21 are an identified priority need group in homelessness legislation.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014, we introduced the ‘Staying Put’ duty, which requires local authorities to support young people in foster care to remain with their former foster carer(s) until age 21. We have also made a commitment to introduce ‘Staying Close’, which will provide many of the benefits associated with Staying Put for young people leaving residential care.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-03-28T16:16:09.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711153/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711153/answer","Children_who_ceased_to_looked_after 2012-2016.xlsx","Children_who_ceased_to_looked_after 2012-2016.xlsx","Children_who_ceased_to_be_looked_after","Children_who_ceased_to_be_looked_after","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711153/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-14","Care Leavers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many young people have left local authority care in each of the last 10 years; and whether they intend to recommend that local authorities treat them as a priority category for social housing.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711154","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-21","<p>Two types of electric trains replace the existing diesel trains on the Great Western Main Line following electrification. Class 387 electric trains replace diesel commuter trains in the Thames Valley. They are brand new trains built by Bombardier to the most modern standards, including in respect of lighting and disabled accessibility. The first are already in service on the route between Hayes &amp; Harlington and Paddington. The other type of train is the Intercity Express, which replaces diesel trains on the long-distance routes from Paddington. This is also a brand new train, built by Hitachi, again to the most modern standards, including in respect of lighting and disabled accessibility.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-03-21T12:29:21.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711154/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711154/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-14","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 14 March, whether the electrification of the Great Western main line will include improved internal lighting in passenger carriages.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711155","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>The UK remains committed to working with our European partners and Turkey to ensure that the EU-Turkey deal is implemented in an effective and sustainable way.</p><p><br>It is clear that the deal continues to represent an important opportunity to effectively manage migratory flows, tackle people smugglers, and prevent people from making perilous crossings.</p><p><br>The EU Commission published its Fifth Report on the Progress in the Implementation of the EU-Turkey Statement on 2<sup>nd</sup> March 2017. The Report concludes that the Statement is continuing to produce tangible results despite difficult circumstances, with an average daily arrival of 43 illegal migrants compared to 1,700 per day in the month before the Statement.</p><p>We continue to believe that Turkey offers sufficient protection, in both its law and its practise, to justify the return migrants from Greece under the EU-Turkey deal. Turkey has modernised its legal framework for the protection of refugees, and the UK has been monitoring the situation closely since the attempted coup. To date, there has not been any evidence of deterioration in the protections or conditions available to refugees.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-23T12:32:51.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711155/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711155/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","EU Immigration: Turkey","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of developments in Turkey, what assessment they have made of the feasibility of applying the EU–Turkey Statement on refugees and migrants, in the form originally prescribed.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711156","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Russian government has a poor record of respecting freedom of expression and enjoys a near monopoly over Russian language media across the post-Soviet region. This provides an avenue for the spreading of disinformation and propaganda.</p><p>Where media plurality exists such as that enjoyed by broadcasters in the UK, the impact is low. Russia Today, for example, has a limited audience share in the UK and we have judged that there is little to no impact measurable from its activity in the West.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-03-28T16:17:16.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711156/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711156/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-14","RT","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of (1) the spread of misinformation, or (2) interference in the internal affairs of foreign states, through the activities of Russia Today.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711157","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-28","<p>National park authorities and Natural England have clear roles with respect to the planning system. National park authorities are required to consult Natural England on development plans and must take into account any advice Natural England provides on them. Natural England is a statutory consultee on development requiring an environmental impact assessment and nationally significant infrastructure projects, and provides advice to national park authorities, local planning authorities and the Secretary of State where it considers there will be significant adverse impacts on national park purposes. In addition, Natural England has a duty to provide advice where any local authority consults it about proposals for the development of land in a national park.</p><p> </p><p>Natural England’s advice is provided in accordance with the National Planning Policy Framework, which affords national parks the highest status of protection in relation to landscape and scenic beauty. Where a local planning authority is minded to grant planning permission contrary to Natural England’s advice, Natural England may request the Secretary of State to call in the application for its determination. Natural England liaises regularly with the Department of Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and the Department for Communities and Local Government on planning and development issues relating to national parks.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-03-28T11:40:32.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711157/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711157/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-14","National Parks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consultations they have had with Natural England about ensuring the protection of the national parks from major development; and what was the outcome of those consultations.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL6045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711158","Department of Health","false","2017-03-27","<p>The Care Act 2014 introduced universal Deferred Payment Agreements (DPAs) so that people should not be forced to sell their homes in their lifetimes to pay for care. The eligibility criteria for DPAs are designed to ensure that they are available to those who would otherwise be at risk of having to sell their homes.</p><p>The Department is continuing to monitor the success of the scheme, and data on the uptake of DPAs across all local authorities will be available later this year.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-27T10:41:13.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711158/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711158/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Care Homes: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of research from Reform indicating that the number of deferred payments issued by local authorities has not risen since 2012, whether they plan to widen access to the Deferred Payment Scheme by raising the £23,500 means threshold.","false","Biography information for Lord Lipsey",,"Lord Lipsey","HL6046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711159","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-27","<p>Whilst the maintenance and renewal of rail infrastructure, including the overhead electricity supply, is a matter for Network Rail overseen by the independent regulator, the Office of Rail and Road, we have regular discussions with Network Rail throughout the year regarding their performance. Future plans for renewal of overhead lines on this route will be set out in Network Rail’s Strategic Business Plan later this year.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-03-27T13:24:29.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711159/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711159/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-14","East Coast Railway Line: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of disruption to services on the East Coast mainline, what recent discussions they have held with Network Rail on its maintenance programme; and when the existing overhead electric wires will be replaced.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL6047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711160","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>Work continues with local authorities and International Partners to deliver the Government’s commitment to resettle 20,000 Syrian refugees over the lifetime of this Parliament and we are on track to do this. Progress on resettlement will be indicated in quarterly immigration statistics. The last set of statistics, published on 23 February showed that 5,454 Syrians were resettled to the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme between October 2015 and December 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-23T12:33:37.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711160/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711160/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are on track to meet their target of resettling 20,000 Syrian refugees into the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement programme by 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL6048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711161","Home Office","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Government has committed to resettling to the UK up to 3,000 individuals under the Vulnerable Children’s Resettlement Scheme over the lifetime of this Parliament. Data on the number of people who have been resettled under this scheme will be published in future releases of the Home Office’s immigration quarterly statistics.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-22T15:00:16.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711161/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711161/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to have resettled 3,000 vulnerable children and their families from the Middle East and North Africa under the Vulnerable Children’s Resettlement Scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL6049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711162","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>The number of unaccompanied asylum seeking children (UASC) arriving in the UK has increased significantly in recent years. This has led to a handful of local authorities caring for a disproportionate number of UASC, principally in those local authority areas where unaccompanied children are first encountered and assessed by the local authority under the Children Act 1989. That is why we introduced the National Transfer Scheme for UASC in July 2016. The National Transfer Scheme is a voluntary scheme which is designed to ensure a more equal distribution of UASC across the country and ensure children are given all the support they need. <br> <br> The National Transfer Scheme has also placed unaccompanied children transferred to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 into local authority care. Following a full consultation with local authorities under section 67 local authorities reported they had capacity for 400 places. <br> <br> Every region in England is participating in the National Transfer Scheme and we are working closely with the Devolved Administrations to ensure they are able to accept cases under the National Transfer Scheme. We are very grateful for the way in which local authorities have stepped up to accept UASC under the National Transfer Scheme. We will continue to work closely with local authorities to take up offers of placements to help ease the burden on those local authorities caring for a disproportionate number of UASC.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-23T12:36:24.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711162/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711162/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Asylum: Children in Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many offers to accommodate unaccompanied young asylum seekers they have received from local authorities; and how many of those offers they (1) have accepted, and (2) propose to accept.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL6050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711163","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>Arms sales data by region are published annually on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes Official Statistics about export licences granted and refused each quarter. The data currently includes details of licences up to 30 September 2016. Data for the period 1 October 2016 to 31 December 2016 will be published on 19 April 2017. The data can be accessed on GOV.UK</p><p> </p><p>Licences granted are not necessarily a measure of exports shipped in a given period as they are valid for between two and five years. Licensing data only provides a partial indication of sales as exporters only declare export values for a subsection of licences (Standard Individual Export Licences). Some licences expire before they are used and in these circumstances exporters must submit a further application, which can result in an element of double counting.</p><p> </p><p>Export values declared for Standard Individual Export Licences for military exports granted in 2010, 2012 and 2014 are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Value (£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>£341,007,088</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£111,721,756</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£80,749,168</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Price",,"2017-03-22T16:19:30.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711163/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711163/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-14","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the value of UK arms sales to Saudi Arabia in (1) 2010, (2) 2012, (3) 2014, and (4) 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL6051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711164","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-22","<p>DFID Yemen’s bilateral funding for Yemen over the last five years is as follows:</p><ul><li>2016/17: £112 million</li><li>2015/16: £89.6 million</li><li>2014/15: £65.9 million</li><li>2013/14: £84.1 million</li><li>2012/13: £59.1 million</li></ul>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-03-22T16:17:59.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711164/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711164/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-14","Yemen: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what aid the UK has provided to Yemen in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL6052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711165","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>We have agreed to undertake a thorough assessment of this matter and are currently considering representations.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-23T12:31:13.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711165/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711165/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-14","Armed Forces: Hong Kong","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the contribution made to Britain by the former Hong Kong Armed Forces from 1857 until 1997, whether, and if so when, they will grant UK passports to the remaining soldiers of the Hong Kong Military Service Corps and the Hong Kong Naval service who did not receive a UK passport following the handover of Hong Kong to China.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711166","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>As set out in the guidance <em>Eliminating mixed sex accommodation in hospitals</em>, it is for each trust to determine how best to accommodate patients, taking into account national guidance on action to eliminate mixed sex accommodation, the relevant quality and safety standards, and patients’ own preferences. A copy of the guidance is attached.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-22T12:21:57.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711166/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711166/answer","MSA guidance.pdf","MSA guidance.pdf","Eliminating mixed sex accommodation","Eliminating mixed sex accommodation","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711166/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-14","Hospital Wards: Gender","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord O’Shaughnessy on 13 March (HL5692), in the context of NHS hospital sleeping accommodation, what is their definition of the opposite sex of (1) men, and (2) women.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL6054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711167","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-21","<p>The V-22 Osprey is not part of the resourced plan to deliver the UK Carrier Strike capability. However, the Ministry of Defence will continue to explore a variety of options to augment the capabilities of the Queen Elizabeth Class carriers in future.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6056 ; HL6057 ; HL6058","2017-03-21T16:52:26.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711167/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711167/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-14","Military Aircraft: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to purchasing V-22 Ospreys to enable air-to-air refuelling of F35B aircraft at the start and end of sorties.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711168","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-21","<p>The V-22 Osprey is not part of the resourced plan to deliver the UK Carrier Strike capability. However, the Ministry of Defence will continue to explore a variety of options to augment the capabilities of the Queen Elizabeth Class carriers in future.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6055 ; HL6057 ; HL6058","2017-03-21T16:52:27.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711168/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711168/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-14","Military Aircraft: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to purchasing V-22 Ospreys to enable long-range high-speed delivery of mission essential spares and stores to the Queen Elizabeth class when deployed.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6056"
